"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nGeneral\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nColchester Gazette: 2:40pm Wednesday 22nd October 2008\n</p>\n<p>\nHeirlooms a reminder of forgotten wartime history\n</p>\n<p>\nAn artefact from a little-known chapter in Colchester\u00e2??s history has been uncovered.\n</p>\n<p>\nFrom 1944 to 1947, 6,000 German prisoners of war were housed in Berechurch Hall Camp, now the Military Corrective Training Centre.\n</p>\n<p>\nStanway resident Cynthia Russell has recently found a book of sketches done by the prisoners at what was known as Camp 186.\n</p>\n<p>\nThe book had been given to Mrs Russell\u00e2??s father Arthur Woolsey, who was superintendent of Colchester Cemetery at the time, and who died 15 years ago.\n</p>\n<p>\n\u00e2??Two of the prisoners came to visit my father whenever a funeral needed organising, and he became friends with them,\u00e2?\u009d Mrs Russell, of Rose Avenue, said.\n</p>\n<p>\n\u00e2??They\u00e2??re such lovely pictures and I will keep them as family heirlooms.\u00e2?\u009d\n</p>\n</div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nGeneral\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nThe Telegraph: 6:14PM BST 23 Oct 2008\n</p>\n<p>\nGerman POW sketches for an English friend found in drawer\n</p>\n<p>\nThe artist, known only as S Arnolds, was one of 6,000 POWs detained at Colchester barracks in Essex from 1944 to 1947.\n</p>\n<p>\nDuring that time former World War One bomber pilot Arthur Woolsey struck up a friendship with Arnolds. He was the head of the town's cemetery and helped arrange funeral for German prisoners from the camp.\n</p>\n<p>\nNow Woolsey's daughter Cynthia Russell, 76, has unearthed the stylish black and white sketches in a drawer after having a spring-clean.\n</p>\n<p>\nThey include pictures of the gateway to St John's Abbey, the Royal Grammar School and 'Theater Camp 186' where Arnolds lived.\n</p>\n<p>\nAs a girl Mrs Russell met the artist and a friend, Bernhard Dieters, who were let out of the camp and allowed to draw Colchester's landmarks.\n</p>\n<p>\nShe said: \"I was about 11 years old and I remember my father met up with two trustees who were prisoners of war.\n</p>\n<p>\n\"They had been trusted to leave the camp and speak to him about funeral arrangements. He became friends with them which is remarkable really.\n</p>\n<p>\n\"He always invited them into the living room rather than the office and my mother would make them a cup of tea.\"\n</p>\n<p>\nOn being repatriated in 1947 they handed over the sketches as a small thank you present, she recalled.\n</p>\n<p>\nHer father, who had 10 children, kept them until his death in 1993. Mrs Russell then took possession of them and put them in a drawer, only to be forgotten for 15 years.\n</p>\n<p>\nShe said her father was injured twice in World War One, once by a bayonet in the foot and the second time when a shell hit his head.\n</p>\n<p>\nHe was later seconded to the RAF and flew bombing raids over Germany in bi-planes.\n</p>\n<p>\nBut she said he never forgot his enemies were human. She said: \"My father was an incredibly compassionate man. He saw the prisoners as men who had been fighting for their country the same as him, and who had been captured. They were human beings to him.\"\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
